Rose Lily
This pinkish lily makes a lady smile. The large flowers are borne on a tall stem clothed with the more or less linear leaves.
Uses: The dried and hashed bulb adds a subtle sweet taste to healing teas and potions.

Morning Glory
The plant entwines itself around structures with its viny stems, growing to a height of 2-3 m tall. The leaves are heart-shaped and the stems are covered with brown hairs. The flowers are trumpet-shaped, predominantly blue to purple or white.
Uses: The buds have great healing properties and are used in many a potion or tincture.
Warning: This plant is hallucinogenic.

Chinchona Tree
Cinchona trees are small trees growing to 5-15 metres tall with evergreen foliage. The leaves are opposite, round, and about 10-40 cm long. The flowers are white, pink or red. The fruit is a small capsule containing numerous seeds.
Use: Bark must be removed carefully in small portions to prevent mold and insect infestation. Used for women in labour to bite on and relieve pain. Fine powder is used in potions.
